- The Members of Parliament elected by the people, the Ministers and the former Presidents have been provided with different entitlements, allowances and privileges such as salaries, allowances, pensions, official quarters, vehicles, staff, office equipment, security personnel etc. The Government has to incur a considerable cost from the public taxes for the provision of said entitlements, allowances and privileges and it has been found the need to reduce this huge expenses within the existing fiscal space. Accordingly, the Cabinet approved the proposal made by the Hon. Prime Minister in her capacity as the Minister of Justice, Public Administration, Home Affairs, Provincial Councils, Local Government and Labour to appoint a Committee with the following composition, to examine the matters in that regard and submit a Report with appropriate recommendations within two (02) months to limit the irrational entitlements, allowances and privileges which are causing an unnecessary burden to the General Treasury on a rational basis or to introduce other suitable alternative methodologies:

*	Justice K.T. Chitrasiri - (Chairman),
  	Retired Judge of the Supreme Court;

*	Mr. D. Dissanayake,
  	Retired Ministry Secretary;

*	Mrs. Jayantha C.T. Bulumulla,
  	Retired District Secretary/Government Agent;

- Due to the indefinite postponement of the Local Authorities Election scheduled to be held on 2023‑03‑09, it has appeared that over 900,000 voters whose names have been included in the Register of Electors updated in the year 2024 are likely to be deprived of their right to vote and to be an election candidature at the upcoming Local Authorities Election. In terms of Article 4 of the Constitution, although, every citizen who has attained 18 years of age and whose name has been entered in the Register of Electors being eligible to be a voter, should be able to exercise his franchise, it has been observed that since calling for nominations for the Local Authorities Election to be held in future has been concluded in January 2023, only voters then registered could cast their votes at the election to be conducted on the said nominations. Similarly, subsequent to the passage of the Local Authorities Election (Amendment) Act No. 30 of 2023, it is required to provide the opportunity for 25% of youth representation in the nomination papers submitted for Local Authorities. Nevertheless, due to the fact that nominations have been called in the year 2023 as of now, 25% of mandatory opportunity for the youth community have been prevented. Therefore, the joint proposal made by the Hon. Prime Minister in his capacity as the Minister of Public Administration, Home Affairs, Provincial Councils and Local Government and the Minister of Justice, Prison Affairs and Constitutional Reforms to instruct the Legal Draftsman to prepare a Local Authorities Elections (Special Provisions) Bill incorporating the appropriate provisions in consultation with the Election Commission so as to receive the necessary authority for the said Commission to re-call for nominations called for the Local Authorities Election 2023 and thereafter to call for nominations to conduct the Local Authorities Election based on the Register of Electors in the year 2024 for - 

      *	protecting the right to vote of the voters whose names have been 	included in the Register of Electors but who have been unable to cast 	their vote at the upcoming Local Authorities Election;

      *	protecting the fundamental right of over 900,000 of voters who are 	youth whose names are included in the 2024 Register of Electors, 	who are likely to be deprived of their right to come forward to 	contest as a candidate at the Election;

      *	protecting the rights of the youth community that may subjected to 	injustice due to deprivation of the quota in contesting as a candidate in 	the Election in terms of the provisions in the Local Authorities Elections 	(Amendment) Act, No.30 of 2023;

was approved by the Cabinet.

