- The Cabinet at its meeting held on 2019 10 29 had granted approval to sign a compact Agreement and a Programme Implementation Agreement between the Millennium Challenge Corporation of the USA and the Government of Sri Lanka to obtain the grant funds provided by the Office of the Millennium Challenge Corporation for the implementation of several programmes of the identified fields. However, taking into consideration the views expressed on the project by various parties, the proposal made by the Hon. Prime Minister to appoint a Committee comprising of the following to make a comprehensive study on the Millennium Challenge Corporation Project and submit recommendations to the Government and to suspend taking action in terms of  the Cabinet decision dated 2019 10 29 in this respect, until such time that the Committee makes its recommendations, was approved by the Cabinet.

*	Prof. Lalithasiri Gunaruwan - (Chairman);

*	Mr. D.S. Jayaweera,
	former Secretary to the Ministry of Transport;

*	Mr. Nihal Jayawardena P.C.; and

*	Mr. Nalaka Jayaweera.

- The proposal made by H.E. the President to appoint the Cabinet Sub Committee on Cost of Living under the Chairmanship of H.E. the President comprising the following members to make recommendations to the Cabinet regarding the matters concerning the cost of living, was approved by the Cabinet.

*	Hon. the Prime Minister in his capacity as the Minister of Finance, Economy and Policy Development;

*	The Minister of Mahaweli, Agriculture, Irrigation and Rural Development and the Minister of Internal Trade, Food Security and Consumer Welfare;

*	The Minister of Fisheries & Aquatic Resources; and

*	The Minister of Plantation Industries and Export Agriculture

It was also decided to appoint a Committee comprising of 06 State Ministers and 12 Officials to assist the said Sub Committee.

- The Cabinet discussed at length about the difficulties faced by the general public owing to the strike initiated by several categories of employees of the Department of Sri Lanka Railways. Accordingly, with a view to finding a satisfactory solution to meet the demands put forward by the relevant trade unions, the Cabinet decided to appoint the following Ministerial Committee under the Chairmanship of Hon.(Dr.) Sarath Amunugama, the Minister of Special Assignments, to conduct discussions with the representatives of the relevant trade unions and make recommendations without any delay for resolving the salaries and other professional issues of the railway employees and  an Officials' Committee comprising of the relevant officers to assist in its deliberations. 

*	Hon. (Dr.) Sarath Amunugama,
	Minister of Special Assignments - (Chairman);

*	Hon. (Dr.) Rajitha Senaratne,
	Minister of Health, Nutrition and Indigenous Medicine;

*	Hon. Ranjith Maddumabandara,
	Minister of Public Administration and Management;

*	Hon. Akila Viraj Kariyawasam, 
	Minister of Education.

- The disruption of cultivation in several seasons, due to the adverse climatic condition that prevailed has resulted in a considerable decline of food production in the country and has caused the escalation of prices of food items. Hon. Ranil Wickremasinghe, the Prime Minister pointed out to the Cabinet that the general public are being severely inconvenienced due to the exorbitant prices of the food items especially such as rice, coconut and vegetables varieties and the Cabinet discussed the matter at length.   

	With a view to controlling this situation, it was decided to take the following measures expeditiously to supply adequate essential food items to the market:

*	to facilitate any Private Institution or the Co-operative Wholesale Establishment (CWE) to import rice under the direction and supervision of the General Treasury;

*	to import the coconut kernel required for the coconut related industries and coconuts required for domestic consumption, under the supervision of the Ministry of Plantation Industries;

*	to appoint an Officials' Committee to submit proposals expeditiously on the further reliefs that could be provided, in addition to the reliefs already granted by the Government,  to the  farmers whose cultivation has been disrupted.

- The Sri Lanka Ports Authority (SLPA), Government of the Democratic Socialist Republic of Sri Lanka (GOSL), China Merchants Port Holdings Company Limited (CM Port), Hambantota International Port Group (Private) Limited (HIPG) and the Hambantota International Port Services Company (Private) Limited (HIPS) entered into a Concession Agreement on 2017-07-29 pertaining to the development of the Hambantota Port by a Public-Private Partnership (PPP).  As per the provisions of the aforesaid Concession Agreement, the relevant parties should fulfill the condition precedents in the Agreement within 180 days from the date of entering into the Agreement and the activities pertaining to same are presently being carried out.   

In terms of clause 4.2 of the Agreement, after completing the condition precedents the CM Port or the affiliated institutions should make the payment, the 'Investment Value' to the Government of Sri Lanka as follows, - 

(i)	an amount of US$ 5 million has already been deposited in a special account as security deposit and the said amount should be transferred to the Sri Lanka Ports Authority on the effective date of the Agreement; 

(ii)	a 10% of the balance Investment Value (tranche 01) should be paid, after deducting the Security Deposit  within  the period of one month from the effective date of the Agreement; 
(iii)	a 30% of the  Investment Value (tranche 02) should be paid within the period of three months from the effective date of the Agreement; 

(iv)	a 60% of the  Investment Value (tranche 03) should be paid within the period of six months from the effective date of the Agreement. 

As requested by the Government of Sri Lanka the CM Port has agreed to advance the date of payment of 'Investment Value' and to increase the amount payable on the effective date of the Agreement as follows - 

(i)	payment of 30% of the remaining balance Investment Value (tranche 01) after deducting the Security Deposit  on the effective date of the Agreement; 

(ii)	payment of 10% (tranche 02) of the Investment Value within the period of one month from the effective date of Agreement; 

(iii)	payment of the balance 60% (tranche 03) of the Investment Value within the period of six months from the effective date of Agreement. 

As such, the proposal made by Hon. Mahinda Samarasinghe, the Minister of Ports and Shipping, to amend the relevant clauses of the Concession Agreement to enable to make the relevant payments as stated above and to sign an Addendum to the Agreement, was approved by the Cabinet.

- Considering the necessity of developing the accommodation facilities in the State Universities available presently, the Government has accorded high priority to develop the infrastructure facilities needed in the Universities.  Accordingly, the proposal made by Hon. Lakshman Kiriella, the Minister of Higher Education and Highways, to implement the following projects at an estimated cost of Rs.380 million between the period from 2018 - 2019, was approved by the Cabinet. 

*	Upgrading the Electrical and Electronic Engineering Department of the Faculty of Engineering of the University of Peradeniya;

*	Construction of a 03 storey hostel building for the foreign students studying at the Bhiksu University of Sri Lanka in Anuradhapura and upgrading its circuit bungalow;

*	Construction of Staff quarters in the Trincomalee Campus of the  Eastern University.

- Ekala area, located closer to the Katunayake, Bandaranaike International Airport, provides a major contribution to the productions of the Industrial Sector in Sri Lanka. It has been designed to implement the following  sub‑projects under the Aero City Development project which is implemented under the Western Region Megapolis Plan. 

*	Establishment of  a reserved area for Value Added industries;

*	Establishment of  a reserved area for Small and Medium Scale Enterprises (SME);

*	Establishment of  a reserved area for commercial and recreational  activities;

*	Media City; and

*	Middle class housing and common amenities. 

The Aero City project inclusive of the above sub‑projects is due to be implemented under the Private Public Partnership basis. Accordingly, the proposal made by Hon. Patali Champika Ranawaka, the Minister of Megapolis and Western Development, to vest the land in extent of 80 acres belonging to the Sri Lanka Broadcasting Corporation to the Urban Development Authority, was approved by the Cabinet.

- The Chronic Kidney Disease of unknown etiology is currently prevalent in 60 Divisional Secretariat Divisions of 11 districts in Sri Lanka and has the possibility of being spread to other areas as well. It has become a serious community health issue and has created a number of social and economic problems as well. Accordingly, the proposal made by H.E. the President Maithripala Sirisena, to implement the following three projects with the collaboration of the Presidential Task Force on Prevention of Chronic Kidney Disease, the Ministry of Health, Nutrition and Indigenous Medicine and other stakeholder agencies  together with the labour contribution of the Sri Lanka Army and the Sri Lanka Navy, with a view to providing a healthcare service with enhanced medical, clinical and patient care facilities for the benefit of  the people affected by the Chronic Kidney Disease (with long term haemodialysis, long term peritoneal dialysis and kidney transplant) at an estimated cost of Rs.462.5 million, was approved by the Cabinet. 

*	Project for the construction of the Kidney Disease Patient Relief Care and Dialysis Centre of Kandy; 

*	Project for the construction of 'Methsirisevana' Kidney Disease Patient Relief Care and Dialysis Centre of Anuradhapura; 

*	Project for the construction of the Centre for Education and Information on Social Welfare and Economic Empowerment related to Kidney Disease in Girandurukotte.

- The implementation of the Gin-Nilwala Diversion Project has commenced with the approval of the Cabinet in the year 2014.  Accordingly, the Engineering, Procurement and Construction contract for the implementation of the Gin-Nilwala Diversion Project has been awarded to a Chinese Company, at a cost of US$ 696 Million.  However, the project had not got off ground since the conditions relating to the Loan Agreement with the Chinese Export and Import Bank had not been finalized. Therefore, the proposal made by Hon. Ravi Karunanayake, the Minister of Finance, to appoint a Ministerial Sub-Committee and an  Officials' Committee comprising of Senior Officials to assist the Sub-Committee, to make an investigation on the following matters relevant to the project, was approved by the Cabinet.   

 *	Whether the contract Agreement can be implemented without any additional cost to the Government;  

*	Assess the negative impact and costs if one party wants to terminate  the Agreement, unilaterally;  

*	Whether the officials associated with the project have violated any financial regulations, government procedures and circular instructions;  and  

*	How to recover the advance payment without any adverse implications.

- H.E. the President Maithripala Sirisena is due to undertake an official visit to Malaysia from 15 - 17 of December, 2016. Therefore, the proposal made by Hon. (Dr.) Harsha de Silva, the Acting Minister of Foreign Affairs, to sign the following Bilateral Instruments with the Government of Malaysia during the above official visit, was approved by the Cabinet. 

*	Memorandum of Understanding 'on Cooperation in Tourism Related Activities';

*	Memorandum of Understanding 'on Cooperation in the Field of Training, Research and Public Administration';

*	Memorandum of Understanding between the Sri Lanka Council for   Agricultural Research Policy and the Malaysian Agricultural Research and Development Institute;

*	Memorandum of Understanding between the Ministry of  Plantation Industries of Sri Lanka and  Ministry of  Plantation Industries and Commodities of the Federation of Malaysia;

*	Memorandum of Understanding 'on Cooperation in the Field of Culture, Arts and Heritage' and

*	Memorandum of Understanding 'on Cooperation in the Field of Youth Development'

- With the implementation of the projects identified under the Master Plan for the Western Region Megapolis, it is anticipated that there will be a greater demand for the utility and infrastructure facilities such as  transport, electricity, water, disposal of waste water and Municipal Solid Waste. Therefore, the proposal made by Hon. Patali Champika Ranawaka, the Minister of Megapolis and Western Development, to take measures to address these challenges, was approved in principle by the Cabinet. 
Interventions to the road network
	*	Extension of Baseline Road up to Galle Road;
*	Polduwa - Koswatta Road under construction to be extended up to Kelaniya via Kolonnawa;
*	Widening of 120 bus route from the Pamankada bridge up to W.A. Silva Mawatha;
*	Construction of a new express transport route to Mahenawatta Science and Techno City from the Multi Modal Transport Hub at Makumbura;
*	Construction of new flyovers at Kohuwala junction and over Castle Street Railway crossing near Castle Hospital;
*	Construction of Multi Modal Transport Hubs at Battaramulla, Katunayake, Kadawatha, Moratuwa and Panadura and regularising the bus transport service to the city; and


*	The proposed elevated road from the Kelani Bridge via Orugodawatta to Rajagiriya to be extended up to the outer circular road covering the Battaramulla Administrative City.

The Cabinet noted that the Ministry of Higher Education and Highways had already taken the preliminary steps to implement some of these projects.
Solid Waste Management
*	Further improving of the Municipal Solid Waste Disposal plants either on sorting or incineration technologies
Ensuring the Essential Water Supply  
*	Construction of larger reservoirs associated with the Seethawaka Ganga and the Vee Oya which are the branches of Kelani Ganga to cater to the increasing demand for drinking water;
*	Recycling of waste water and use for other activities other than for drinking; and
*	Desalination of sea water by obtaining electricity from the power stations at off peak periods.	

Further, the Cabinet noted that the Water Resources Board has already taken measures to utilise more ground water than presently used for industrial purposes, with the objective of saving the river waters for the supply of drinking water and also that the Board is already in the process experimenting with regard to artificial introduction of ground water beds.

- The proposals made by the Prime Minister, Hon. Ranil Wickremasinghe, in his capacity as the Minister of National Policies and Economic Affairs and Hon. (Dr.) Harsha de Silva, the Acting Minister of Foreign Affairs, to sign the following Memoranda of Understanding (MoUs) between Sri Lanka and Pakistan, during the scheduled visit to Sri Lanka by the Prime Minister of Pakistan, H.E. Nawaz Sharif, in the first week of January 2016, was approved by the Cabinet: 

